<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910418-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>910418-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Stanley Works:   First-Quarter Net Income   Fell 31% to $15.5 Million</HL><DATE>04/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   SWK</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)</RE><LP>   Stanley Works, a New Britain, Conn., maker of tools andhardware, said first-quarter net income fell 31% to $15.5million, or 38 cents a share, on lower sales.   The company blamed lackluster consumer spending andbuilding activity for weak sales, which dropped to $453.6million from $484.1 million a year ago.</LP><TEXT>   Year-ago earnings were $22.5 million, or 53 cents a share.The year-earlier period included a gain of $10 million fromthe sale of the company's drapery hardware business, whichwas partially offset by a $7.1 million charge for contingentliability reserves.   &quot;We have felt for some time that the last half of 1990 andthe first quarter of 1991 would be the toughest economicconditions for our businesses,&quot; said Richard H. Ayers,chairman and chief executive officer. &quot;We hope that this willprove to be the case.&quot;   Meanwhile, Mr. Ayers announced that the company was &quot;inthe process&quot; of acquiring Nirva, a Lille, France, maker ofclosets. Although details weren't disclosed, Mr. Ayers saidNirva would provide &quot;a strong base for extending sales of(Stanley's) Acmetrack and other hardware products in Europe.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>